\f0\fs66 \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 Monotype Compositions is a project involving the diary of WW1 nurse Clarice Spratling, historical print technology, and data sonification.\ Conceived by artist and printmaker Dawn Cole [1], who wrote: "I had begun [...] to wonder if I could somehow \'91play\'92 the monotype spool in a specially designed music box. What would the sound of Clarice\'92s diary be like played in this way? Would it bear any resemblance to word sounds when read aloud or have a pattern that would reference the lace patterns I had created using the written words?" [2].\ We have made a 3D-printed device to record a digital video of the Monotype tape, and Python software using OpenCV [3] to extract typesetting data from the video. Using ideas from Prof. David De Roure's \i Numbers into Notes \i0 [4], we will explore ways in which the data can be presented sonically through translation to MIDI, in turn to inform a design for Dawn's "specially designed music box".}
